USED CAR SALES DATA ANALYSIS

PROBLEM STATEMENT

As we know, this year the prices of cars ranging from Maruti, Tata Motors to Mercedes and Audi has increased because of higher input costs and many other reasons. Due to the incapability of customers to buy new cars, mostly due to the lack of funds more and more people are now shifting to buying used cars. So in this project we are going to assume a company whose used car sales has been down since the prices rose up even though the sales of used cars is showing a global increase. We will use a used car price prediction system to assist the company in increasing its used car sales by making changes to the features that are causing their low sales.

MOTIVATION

We as a team were required to find a topic that was in common interest to all of us. It so happened to be that Automobile industry was a field in which all of us had a basic idea and hence tried getting datasets that were related to the same. Automobile Industry being one of the largest fields, the datasets related to the same were unlimited and humongous in size. We were in search of a dataset which would be both helpful in exploring the data to the maximum and learn as much as possible from the same .Thus we found out the dataset related to used car sales data which contained the required data for which Exploratory Data Analysis can be done.

6.1 Fixing engV missing / erroneous values

In [85]:
#Function that removes the outlier entries of engV and returns dataframe

def exclude_outliers_for_engV():
    return pd.DataFrame(carsales[(carsales.engV > 0.5) & (carsales.engV < 25)])

# Function that computes the mean value of engV based on make and model 

def compute_engV_mean(r):
    car_make = r.name[0]    
    car_model = r.name[1]
    if r.count() > 0:
        return round(r.mean(),2)
    else:
        engV_df = exclude_outliers_for_engV()
        engV_make = engV_df[engV_df.car == car_make].engV
        if engV_make.count() > 0:
            return round(engV_make.mean(),2)
        else:
            return round(engV_df.engV.mean(),2)
        

#Create a staging "engV mean" dataframe for  all combinations of make and model

engV_mean = carsales.groupby(['car','model']).engV.apply(compute_engV_mean).reset_index()
engV_mean.rename(columns={'engV':'engV_avg'}, inplace=True)
engV_mean.head(5)

'''
Function that return engV value for missing records
'''
def get_missing_engV(r):
    if pd.isnull(r.engV):
        return engV_mean[(engV_mean.car == r.car) & (engV_mean.model == r.model)].engV_avg.values[0]
    else:
        return r.engV
    

'''
Fix the missing engV values
'''
print('--------------Before fix-----------------')
print(carsales[carsales.engV.isnull()].shape)

carsales.engV = carsales.apply(get_missing_engV, axis=1)
print('--------------After fix -----------------')
print(carsales[carsales.engV.isnull()].shape)

In [87]:
#Function that computes the median value of price based on make and model 

def compute_price_median(r):
    car_make = r.name[0]    
    car_model = r.name[1]
    if (r.count() > 0) & (r.median() > 0):
        return r.median()
    else:
        price_make = carsales[carsales.car == car_make].price
        if price_make.median() > 0:
            return price_make.median()
        else:
            return carsales.price.median()

        
'''
Create a staging "Price median" dataframe for  all combinations of make and model
'''
price_median = carsales.groupby(['car','model']).price.apply(compute_price_median).reset_index()
price_median.rename(columns={'price':'price_median'}, inplace=True)

6.4 Fixing drive missing / erroneous values

In [91]:
# Function that removes the null entries of drive and returns dataframe

def get_clensed_data_for_drive():
    return pd.DataFrame(carsales[carsales.drive.isnull() == False])



# Function that computes the mode value of drive based on make and model 

def compute_drive(r):
    car_make = r.name[0]    
    car_model = r.name[1]
    if r.count() > 0:
        return r.mode()
    else:
        drive_df = get_clensed_data_for_drive()
        drive_make = drive_df[drive_df.car == car_make].drive
        if drive_make.count() > 0:
            return drive_make.mode()
        else:
            return drive_df.drive.mode()
        
        

# Create a staging "drive mode" dataframe for  all combinations of make and model

drive_mode = carsales.groupby(['car','model']).drive.apply(compute_drive).reset_index()
drive_mode.rename(columns={'drive':'drive_mode'}, inplace=True)
drive_mode.drop('level_2', axis=1)

#Function that returns perticular year sales

def get_SalesByYear(year):
    return carsales_year_df[carsales_year_df.year == year]


# Function that returns rank of a car

def get_CarSalesRankByYear(r):
    result = get_SalesByYear(r.year).sales.unique()
    i, = np.where(result == r.sales)
    return i[0]+1

In [120]:
'''
Fuction that computes the class of the car based on price
Rules:
    -- Economy --> Price less than 10000 
    -- Luxury  --> Price above 10000 and below 30000
    -- Premium --> Price above 30000
'''
def classify_class(r):
    if r.price <= 10000:
        return "Economy"
    elif (r.price > 10000) & (r.price <= 30000):
        return "Luxury"
    else:
        return "Premium"
    
    # Set new column called 'class' for defining the sement

carsales["class"] = carsales.apply(classify_class, axis=1)

In [138]:
# Return upper whisker for mileage by class
def get_best_carandmileage_byclass(cls):
    clsmileage = besteconomycars[besteconomycars['class'] == cls]
    maxval = clsmileage.mileage.max()
    thirdQurtile = clsmileage.describe().iloc[6].mileage   
    firstQurtile = clsmileage.describe().iloc[4].mileage     
    iqr = thirdQurtile - firstQurtile
    upperwhisker = min(maxval, thirdQurtile + (1.5 * iqr))
    return upperwhisker

# Get closest upper whisker milage results
def get_closest(cls, val):
    cls_df = carsales[carsales['class'] == cls]
    return cls_df.iloc[(cls_df['mileage']-val).abs().argsort()[:2]]

Insights¶

Sense the customer likelyhood and market more such cars.

1 Petrol and Diesel cars are most popular.

2Full wheel drive is most preferred in Crossovers and Front wheel drive in Sedan cars

3 So bring more inventory from most value for money branded cars like Mercedes-Benz, Toyota, BMW, Volkswagen etc.. Crossovers with Full wheel drive Sedans with front wheel drive

4 Luxury and Premium used cars booming sales due to hike in new car prices.

-->Market & Procure more latest, future ready and sophisticated cars like Engine type other (Hybrid and Electric cars). Despite the fact that car sales fluctuated across years, the Other cars sales are consistent and seen ramp up in sales recently.

-->Economy cars are ideally most selling. And most recent economy car are gas engines which are not preferred by customers. So procure more Economy price range cars which is of Petrol or Diesel engine types
